Course Content

Story of Ayurveda

Ayurveda is more than just medicine; it is the ancient Indian "Science of Life." Its goal is simple: to teach us how to live happily, healthily, and in perfect balance with the world around us. For thousands of years, this knowledge has been passed down through an incredible lineage, starting from the universe's creator himself.


The Divine Source and the Chain of Knowledge

The origin of Ayurveda is believed to be divine. The transfer of this sacred knowledge, from the gods to the human sages, is beautifully captured in a famous Sanskrit verse.


.

brahm smtv''yuo veda prajpatimajigrahat

so'vinau tau sahasrka so'triputrdiknmnn

te'gnivedikste tu pthak tantri tenire.


Meaning: "Bhagavan Brahma remembered the Veda of life (Ayurveda) and taught it to Prajpati. He (Prajpati) taught it to the twin Ashvinau (the divine physicians), they taught it to Sahasrka (Bhagavan Indra), he taught it to Atriputra and other sages. And they, in turn, taught it to Agnivea and others, who then created separate treatises (texts)."


So, the knowledge began with Bhagavan Brahma and traveled down through celestial beings like Indra, the twin Ashvinau, and eventually reached human sages like Agnivea, whose writings form the basis of Ayurveda today.


The Churning of the Ocean and Dhanvantari

Another central part of Ayurveda's story involves the spectacular event called the Samudra Manthan (The Churning of the Ocean). Long ago, the Devas (celestials) and Asuras (demons) worked together to churn the cosmic ocean to obtain Amrita, the nectar of immortality.

They used Mount Mandara as the churning rod and the great serpent Vasuki as the rope. As they churned for a long time, many incredible treasures emergedfrom beautiful celestial beings to lethal poison. Finally, out of the deep, swirling water, the magnificent figure of Bhagavan Dhanvantari appeared. He was glowing and carried a Kalasha (pot) filled with the life-giving Amrita.

Bhagavan Dhanvantari is celebrated as the original God of Medicine and the divine source of all healing in Ayurveda. He taught the world how to use natures gifts to stay well.



The Birth and Legacy of the Divine Physician

Though Bhagavan Dhanvantari first appeared from the cosmic ocean, the world needed him to share his wisdom directly with humanity. Bhagavan Vishnu informed the gods that Dhanvantari would return to Earth to teach Ayurveda.


This happened when Raja Dirghatamas of Kashi (Varanasi) performed prayers and wished for a special boon. When Bhagavan Dhanvantari appeared before him, the Raja requested that the Lord be born as his own son. The wish was granted.


Bhagavan Dhanvantari was reborn into the royal family of Kashi. Even as a child, he showed great self-control and deep wisdom, focusing on learning and spiritual practice. When he became Raja, he also served as the ultimate teacher of healing. Great sages and scholars, including the famous Sushruta, who is known as the Father of Surgery, became his disciples and learned the deepest secrets of Ayurveda from him. These profound lessons are recorded in ancient texts like the Agni Purana.


Today, Bhagavan Dhanvantari is worshipped all over India as the God of Medicine. To celebrate his divine birth, people observe Dhanvantari Jayanti every year on Dhanteras, just two days before the festival of Diwali. On this night, a Diya (lamp) facing north-east is lit at the door to welcome Bhagavan Dhanvantari and pray for good health and happiness, as scriptures promise release from all diseases for those who pray to him.
